f:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Drift calculates ATOM/USDT funding rates every hour using a hybrid vAMM and DLOB model that adjusts based on perp-spot price divergence. The exchange's JIT liquidity auctions help maintain tight spreads, while the insurance fund provides additional stability for rate calculations. Funding payments occur precisely every hour, with rates determined by the 8-hour TWAP of the premium between perpetual and spot prices. Drift's Solana-based architecture enables near-instant settlement with minimal gas costs for frequent funding payments."}]
10:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","ATOM","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ATOM/USDT represents a strategic arbitrage opportunity as Cosmos Hub's interchain narrative drives periodic volatility spikes that can create significant funding rate divergences. The token's L1 status attracts both retail and institutional interest, leading to imbalanced positioning that generates profitable funding rate environments. Drift's lower fees compared to centralized exchanges make ATOM arbitrage particularly attractive for capturing these rate differentials."}]]}]
11:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"ATOM Funding Rate Patterns on Drift"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ATOM funding rates on Drift typically range from -0.01% to 0.05% per hour, with elevated rates during Cosmos ecosystem announcements or IBC protocol updates. The token shows pronounced funding spikes during interchain development milestones, often reaching 0.1%+ hourly rates when retail sentiment turns bullish. Historical data indicates funding rates tend to normalize within 24-48 hours as arbitrageurs capitalize on elevated premiums. Drift's 1-hour funding cycle allows for more granular rate movements compared to 8-hour cycles on traditional exchanges."}]]}]
12:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Strategy"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Drift's ATOM/USDT funding presents arbitrage opportunities through rate differentials with major CEXs like Binance and OKX, particularly during Cosmos-specific news events. The exchange's vAMM model can create temporary inefficiencies when large positions shift the funding rate calculation, offering short-term arbitrage windows. Cross-exchange strategies work effectively by longing ATOM on Drift during negative funding periods while shorting on exchanges with positive rates. Drift's low 0.02% maker fees enhance arbitrage profitability, especially for high-frequency strategies targeting funding rate convergence."}]]}]
13:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations for Drift ATOM Trading"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Solana network dependency represents the primary risk, as congestion or downtime can prevent timely position adjustments during volatile funding periods. Drift's liquidation mechanics involve a complex oracle system that may behave differently than CEX liquidations during extreme market stress. The exchange's lower liquidity compared to major centralized venues means large positions can significantly impact funding rate calculations. Insurance fund coverage, while robust, may face pressure during cascade liquidation events affecting ATOM positions across the Solana ecosystem."}]]}]
14:["$","$L16",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often are ATOM funding rates calculated on Drift?","answer":"Drift calculates ATOM/USDT funding rates every hour using an 8-hour TWAP of the premium between perpetual and spot prices. Payments are settled automatically at the top of each hour with near-instant finality on Solana."},{"question":"What makes Drift's ATOM funding different from CEX rates?","answer":"Drift's vAMM and DLOB hybrid model creates more responsive funding rate adjustments compared to traditional order book exchanges. The 1-hour cycle allows for faster rate normalization, while JIT liquidity auctions help maintain competitive premiums throughout the funding period."},{"question":"Can I arbitrage ATOM funding between Drift and other exchanges?","answer":"Yes, cross-exchange arbitrage is possible by taking opposing positions on Drift versus CEXs during funding rate divergences. Drift's low fees and Solana's speed make this particularly effective, though you must account for bridge delays when moving collateral between networks."},{"question":"What are the main risks of ATOM funding arbitrage on Drift?","answer":"Primary risks include Solana network congestion affecting position management, lower liquidity creating slippage on larger trades, and complex liquidation mechanics that may differ from CEX behavior. Monitor the insurance fund status and network performance during volatile periods."}]}]
